const STATIC_TRANSCRIPTS_devops_t1 = [
  "CI means developers merge their code frequently and automated tests run on every commit to catch integration bugs early. Continuous delivery means the codebase is always in a releasable state and deployment to production can happen with a button press. Continuous deployment goes further and automatically ships every passing build to production without any manual gate.",
  "Docker solves the it works on my machine problem by packaging the application and all its dependencies into a container image. Unlike a traditional server setup where library versions clash, each container is isolated. You define the environment once in a Dockerfile and it runs identically on a developer laptop and in production.",
  "Docker gets a single container running but does not handle running hundreds of them, restarting crashed ones, distributing traffic, or rolling updates. Kubernetes orchestrates a fleet of containers across multiple nodes. It schedules pods, ensures desired replica counts, exposes services, and provides self-healing if a node goes down.",
  "Infrastructure as Code means your servers, networks, and databases are defined in version-controlled files rather than set up manually. Terraform provisions the underlying infrastructure declaratively, you describe what you want and it figures out how to get there. Ansible then configures the running servers using imperative playbooks.",
  "A typical pipeline starts when a developer pushes code. The CI server builds the application, runs unit and integration tests, then runs a linter. If all pass it packages the artifact as a Docker image and pushes it to a registry. A deploy stage then updates the staging environment and after manual or automated approval it deploys to production.",
  "A virtual machine includes a full guest operating system running on top of a hypervisor. This means hundreds of megabytes of overhead and slow boot times. A container shares the host OS kernel so it starts in milliseconds and uses far less memory. VMs are better for full OS isolation or running different operating systems; containers are better for microservices.",
  "A reverse proxy sits in front of your application servers and forwards client requests to them. Nginx as a reverse proxy handles SSL termination so the backend only needs to deal with plain HTTP. It also load balances across multiple upstream instances, caches static responses, and protects the backend from direct internet exposure.",
  "Blue-green deployments run two identical production environments. You deploy to green while blue serves traffic, verify green is healthy, then switch the load balancer. Rollback is instant by pointing back to blue. Canary deployment routes a small percentage of traffic to the new version first, gradually increasing it. This limits the blast radius of a bad release.",
  "The Dockerfile starts with a FROM Node image. I copy the package.json first and run npm install before copying the rest of the source code. This exploits Docker layer caching so dependencies are only reinstalled when package.json changes. EXPOSE declares the port and CMD specifies the startup command.",
  "Observability is the ability to understand internal system state from external outputs. Logs are discrete time-stamped events recording what happened. Metrics are aggregated numerical measurements over time like request rate or error rate. Traces follow a single request through multiple services showing where latency was spent. All three together give you a complete picture.",
  "A Pod is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes and wraps one or more containers. A Deployment manages a set of identical Pods, ensuring the desired number of replicas are running and handling rolling updates. A Service provides a stable DNS name and load balances traffic across the Pods behind it regardless of which node they are on.",
  "When you type a URL, the browser checks its local DNS cache first. If not found it queries the recursive resolver provided by your ISP or a public one like 8.8.8.8. The resolver walks from root servers to TLD nameservers like .com to authoritative nameservers for the domain to get the final IP address which is returned to the browser.",
  "Layer 4 load balancing works at the transport level using TCP and UDP without inspecting the request content. It is very fast and low overhead. Layer 7 operates at the application layer, reading HTTP headers, URLs, and cookies. This allows routing based on path so requests to slash API go to backend servers while slash static goes to a CDN origin.",
  "The principle of least privilege means every service or user gets only the minimum permissions needed to do its job. In AWS I create IAM roles with specific policies for each service rather than giving admin access. An EC2 instance that only reads from S3 should have a role with only GetObject on that specific bucket.",
  "A message queue decouples the producer from the consumer. Unlike a direct REST call where the caller waits for a response, a queue stores messages so consumers process them asynchronously at their own pace. RabbitMQ is a traditional broker for task queues. Kafka is a distributed log designed for high throughput and durable event streaming across many consumers.",
  "The Horizontal Pod Autoscaler watches a target metric such as average CPU utilisation across Pods. When the metric exceeds a threshold the HPA calculates how many replicas are needed and scales the Deployment up. When load drops it scales back down after a cooldown period. You can also configure custom metrics from Prometheus for more sophisticated scaling.",
  "SSH uses asymmetric cryptography. You generate a key pair: the private key stays on your machine and the public key is placed in the server's authorized_keys file. When you connect the server sends a challenge encrypted with your public key. Only you can decrypt it with your private key and send back the correct response, proving identity without a password.",
  "A VPC is a logically isolated network in the cloud. Within it you create public subnets with internet gateway access for load balancers and private subnets without direct internet access for application servers and databases. Security groups act as stateful firewalls at the instance level, controlling inbound and outbound traffic by port and IP range.",
  "Immutable infrastructure means once a server is deployed you never patch or modify it. If you need a change you build a new image, deploy instances from it, and terminate the old ones. This eliminates configuration drift where servers gradually diverge from their intended state. Rollback is as simple as redeploying the previous image.",
  "GitOps uses Git as the single source of truth for both application code and infrastructure configuration. Tools like ArgoCD continuously compare the desired state in Git with the actual cluster state and automatically reconcile differences. Unlike traditional CI/CD where a pipeline pushes changes, GitOps pulls and applies them declaratively.",
];

