const STATIC_TRANSCRIPTS_ml_t1 = [
  "Supervised learning trains a model on labelled input-output pairs to predict outputs for new inputs. Examples include regression and classification. Unsupervised learning finds patterns in unlabelled data like clustering and dimensionality reduction. Reinforcement learning trains an agent through trial and error using a reward signal to guide behaviour.",
  "Overfitting is when a model learns the training data too well including its noise and fails to generalise. You detect it when training accuracy is high but validation accuracy is low. Prevention techniques include regularisation, dropout, early stopping, and more training data. Underfitting is when the model is too simple and performs poorly on both train and validation sets.",
  "Bias is error from incorrect assumptions in the learning algorithm, causing it to miss relevant relationships. Variance is error from sensitivity to small fluctuations in training data. A high bias model underfits; a high variance model overfits. The trade-off means reducing bias often increases variance. The goal is finding the complexity that balances both for good generalisation.",
  "Gradient descent iteratively adjusts model parameters in the direction that minimises the loss function. Batch gradient descent computes the gradient over the entire dataset, which is stable but slow. Stochastic uses one random sample per update, fast but noisy. Mini-batch uses a small subset, balancing speed and stability. Most deep learning uses mini-batch with batch sizes like 32 or 256.",
  "Cross-validation estimates how well a model generalises to unseen data. K-fold splits the data into k folds and trains k times, each time using a different fold as validation and the rest as training. The k validation scores are averaged for a reliable estimate. This is more robust than a single train-val split, especially for small datasets.",
  "Precision is the fraction of positive predictions that are actually positive. Recall is the fraction of actual positives that were correctly identified. F1 is their harmonic mean. In cancer detection I would prioritise recall because missing a real case is far worse than a false alarm. In spam detection I might prioritise precision to avoid marking legitimate emails as spam.",
  "A confusion matrix is a grid showing true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives. From it you derive precision, recall, accuracy, and specificity. It is particularly useful for imbalanced classes where accuracy alone can be misleading. For a dataset with 99 percent negatives a model predicting all negatives is 99 percent accurate but useless.",
  "Regularisation adds a penalty term to the loss function to discourage overly complex models. L1 or Lasso adds the absolute value of weights, encouraging sparsity by pushing some weights to exactly zero, effectively performing feature selection. L2 or Ridge adds the square of weights, shrinking all weights toward zero without eliminating them completely.",
  "Activation functions introduce non-linearity, without which a neural network regardless of depth collapses to a single linear transformation. ReLU returns zero for negative inputs and the input for positive inputs, which is computationally simple and avoids the vanishing gradient problem. Sigmoid and tanh saturate at extremes causing gradients to vanish. Softmax converts outputs to probabilities for multi-class classification.",
  "Classification predicts a discrete label such as spam or not spam, cat or dog. Regression predicts a continuous value such as house price or temperature. The loss functions differ: classification typically uses cross-entropy, regression uses mean squared error. Evaluation metrics also differ: accuracy and F1 for classification, RMSE and MAE for regression.",
  "Feature engineering transforms raw data into inputs that better represent the underlying problem to the model. This includes encoding categorical variables, scaling numerical features, creating polynomial features, and extracting domain-specific signals. A well-engineered feature set can make a simple model outperform a complex one on poor features.",
  "Bagging trains multiple models in parallel on different random subsets of the training data and averages their predictions. This reduces variance. Random Forest is the classic bagging algorithm using decision trees with random feature subsets. Boosting trains models sequentially where each new model corrects the errors of the previous one, reducing bias. XGBoost and LightGBM are the leading boosting frameworks.",
  "CNNs use convolutional filters that slide over input images detecting local patterns like edges, textures, and shapes. Because the same filter is applied everywhere the network learns translation-invariant features with far fewer parameters than a fully connected network. Pooling layers reduce spatial dimensions preserving the most important information. Deep CNNs stack these to detect increasingly abstract features.",
  "Transfer learning reuses the weights of a model pre-trained on a large dataset and fine-tunes it for a new task. For images, models pre-trained on ImageNet already know how to detect edges, textures, and objects. You replace only the final classification layer and retrain on your small dataset. This dramatically reduces training time and data requirements.",
  "The attention mechanism allows the model to weigh the importance of different positions in the input when generating each output token. Instead of compressing the entire input into a fixed vector, attention queries the full input sequence and focuses on the most relevant parts. Transformers use self-attention to build context-aware representations of each token relative to all others.",
  "Discriminative models learn the conditional probability of the label given the input, the decision boundary between classes. Examples are logistic regression and SVMs. Generative models learn the joint probability of data and labels and can generate new samples. Examples are VAEs and GANs. Generative models can handle missing data and generate synthetic examples.",
  "I would first try oversampling the minority class using SMOTE which creates synthetic examples by interpolating between existing ones. Alternatively I would use the class_weight parameter in scikit-learn to penalise misclassifying the minority class more heavily. I would evaluate using F1 score and AUC-ROC rather than accuracy to avoid misleading results.",
  "PCA projects data onto the directions of maximum variance called principal components. It reduces dimensionality by keeping only the top k components that explain most of the variance. Use cases include reducing noise, visualising high-dimensional data in 2D, and speeding up training. The trade-off is interpretability since components are linear combinations of original features.",
  "The ROC curve plots true positive rate against false positive rate at every possible decision threshold. AUC is the area under this curve. An AUC of 1.0 means perfect classification, 0.5 means no better than random. AUC is threshold-independent so it measures overall discriminative ability. I use it when comparing models or when the optimal threshold is not yet known.",
  "In deep networks gradients are multiplied through many layers during backpropagation. If activations like sigmoid saturate, their gradients approach zero and the signal vanishes before reaching early layers, making training very slow. ReLU avoids this for positive activations. Batch normalisation stabilises activations. Residual connections create shortcuts that let gradients flow directly to earlier layers.",
];

